1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:02,352
Eighty-six percent.

2
00:00:02,302 --> 00:00:06,763
That's how much of render time Chrome spends just taking screenshots.

3
00:00:06,763 --> 00:00:09,578
The native renderer changes that.

4
00:00:09,578 --> 00:00:13,052
H T M L stays the authoring format.

5
00:00:13,052 --> 00:00:18,631
A Rust and Skia I R replaces the per-frame browser path for the subset we control.

6
00:00:18,631 --> 00:00:24,986
The auto backend chooses transparently — native when the compiler can prove support, Chrome when it can't.

7
00:00:24,986 --> 00:00:27,394
Every decision is logged.

8
00:00:27,394 --> 00:00:29,960
Nothing changes silently.

9
00:00:29,960 --> 00:00:36,171
Adapters compile known primitives into a deterministic I R. G-SAP stays canonical.

10
00:00:36,171 --> 00:00:41,092
Text runs through Chrome once, cached as glyph clips, then composited.

11
00:00:41,092 --> 00:00:43,171
Seven phases.

12
00:00:43,171 --> 00:00:47,144
Starting with proof infrastructure — not speed claims.

13
00:00:47,144 --> 00:00:50,078
Can we detect support accurately?

14
00:00:50,078 --> 00:00:52,723
Can we prove quality gates?

15
00:00:52,723 --> 00:00:55,618
Can the auto backend be trusted?

16
00:00:55,618 --> 00:00:58,039
Then we grow the subset.

17
00:00:58,039 --> 00:01:00,513
One fixture at a time.

18
00:01:00,513 --> 00:01:03,763
Native rendering isn't replacing Chrome.

19
00:01:03,763 --> 00:01:07,644
It's giving the best HyperFrames work a faster lane.

20
00:01:07,644 --> 00:01:09,828
Let's build it right.

